d208c-21 | 2026-06-09T12:28:12Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 |  \n | Fabric | project *list* source | *description* source | authority / consistency | \n |--------|----------------------|---------------------|------------------------| \n | **nip29** | groups the agent belongs to (reverse of `39002`) / relay group enumeration | relay-authored `kind:39000` group metadata | **canonical & shared** — one source, all machines agree | \n | **mls** | MLS groups in local state | group-context extension / a metadata message | **member-authored**, cryptographically scoped to the group | \n | **kind1** | *derived*: observed `t`-tags + local list of dirs you've run in | **none native** → local descriptor file or a self-published note | **client-local** — two machines can disagree; eventually-divergent | \n  \n The sharp edge is kind1: groups are just `t`-tags, so there is **no native carrier for a description and no authoritative project registry**. The domain must therefore tolerate `description: Option<String>` and accept that for some fabrics the list is *derived/observed* rather than *enumerated*, and metadata is local-only. That's the same class of concession as kind1's client-side membership enforcement — it's not a flaw in the abstraction, it's the abstraction correctly surfacing that the fabric has no shared truth here. [...] "Different ways to retrieve" cuts along a second axis the design already supports — **pull vs. live**: \n  \n - **nip29/mls** can do both: one-shot fetch the `39000` metadata, *or* subscribe to it (it's replaceable) so a description you edit on another machine propagates with zero domain changes — the same live-membership trick. \n - **kind1** is whatever the local mechanism is (file watch, or re-derive from observed events). \n  \n That maps cleanly onto the **Delivery** + **Membership-style source** capabilities: `project_meta` becomes a `(query_once, subscribe_changes)` pair, owned by the provider, identical in shape to how `roster`/`is_member` relate.
d208c-22 | 2026-06-09T12:28:12Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 |  \n `list_agents()` is another `(query, stream)` view off the **State-source** capability, with the same per-fabric source variation and the same kind1 concession: \n  \n | Fabric | agent-list source | scope | \n |--------|-------------------|-------| \n | nip29 | members of the group(s) you're in (reverse of `39002`) → pubkeys | per-group | \n | mls | the MLS group roster keys | per-group | \n | kind1 | *derived* — observed event authors carrying an `agent` tag, ∪ the local whitelist | global (no group) | \n  \n And the kind1 fallback is identical to projects: the list is *derived* not *enumerated*, and an agent's card may not have been observed yet → partial/`Option`. So: same shape, same provider-owned source, same derived/Option degradation. ✅
d208c-23 | 2026-06-09T12:28:16Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | ## The asymmetry: agent identity is self-sovereign, project metadata isn't \n  \n This is where "the same, right?" needs a caveat. For **projects**, the *authority* over metadata varies by fabric — a nip29 description is **relay-authored** (`39000`), one canonical shared value. For **agents**, the identity card (slug, host, owners) is **self-authored on every fabric** — the agent signs its own profile (today: self-authored `kind:0`). The relay, the MLS group, nobody else authors your slug or host. Identity is `(agent, machine)` with a sovereign key; the fabric never *grants* it. \n  \n So for agents the interesting per-fabric variation moves **off** the "who authored the metadata" axis (always the agent itself) and **onto** two others: \n  \n 1. **Discovery / scope** — how you find agents, and whether the list is group-scoped (nip29/mls) or global-derived (kind1). *(Same axis as project enumeration.)* \n 2. **Authorization** — whether to *trust and show* an agent. The card p-tags an owner; you accept it only if that owner is in your ACL/whitelist. That's the owner-claim → ACL check (the deliberately not-author-restricted profile-discovery filter already in `kind1.rs`). This is the agent analogue of project membership's *enforcement-locus*. \n  \n **One-liner:** agent **list** = same as projects (uniform shape, provider source, derived/Option fallback). Agent **metadata** = same query/stream mechanics, but provenance is *uniformly self-sovereign*, so the per-fabric axis that matters is **discovery + owner-claim authorization**, not "who authored the description."
